ionship between sexism, racism, and economic inequality; yet, they are virtually unknown in American political thought because they are considered activists, not theorists. Their efforts to expand the reach of America’s founding ideals laid the groundwork not only for women’s suffrage and the abolition of slavery, but for the broader expansion of civil, political, and human rights that would characterize much of the twentieth century and continues to unfold today. Drawing on a careful reading of speeches, letters and other archival sources, Lisa Pace Vetter shows the ways in which the early women’s rights movement and abolitionism were central to the development of American political thought. The Political Thought of America’s Founding Feminists demonstrates that early American political thought is incomplete without attention to these important female thinkers, and that an understanding of early American women’s movements is incomplete without considering its profound impact on political thought. A complex and thoughtful guide to the indispensable role of women in shaping the American way of life, The Political Thought of America’s Founding Feminists is essential for a comprehensive understanding of the history of American political thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFeminism - United States - History - 19th century. 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFeministszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aVetter, Lisa Pace, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107289720 cprintz978147985334240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479853342.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479867752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/